roducts such as Coca Cola, Worcestershire Sauce, and Palmolive Soap rely on African plants that were brought to the Americas on slave ships as provisions, medicines, cordage, and bedding. In this exciting, original, and groundbreaking book, Judith A. Carney and Richard Nicholas Rosomoff draw on archaeological records, oral histories, and the accounts of slave ship captains to show how slaves' food plots—"botanical gardens of the dispossessed"—became the incubators of African survival in the Americas and Africanized the foodways of plantation societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBlack peoplexEthnobotanyzAfricaxHistory. 0aBlack peoplexEthnobotanyzAmericaxHistory. 0aBlacksxEthnobotanyzAfricaxHistory. 0aBlacksxEthnobotanyzAmericaxHistory. 0aEnslaved personszAmericaxHistory. 0aEthnobotanyzAfricaxHistory. 0aEthnobotanyzAmericaxHistory. 0aMedicinal plantszAfricaxHistory. 0aMedicinal plantszAmericaxHistory. 0aPlants, EdiblezAfricaxHistory. 0aPlants, EdiblezAmericaxHistory. 0aSlaveszAmericaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Africa / General.2bisacsh  aafrica.  aafrican american history.  aafrican dispora.  aafrican history.  aafrican plants.  aafrican slaves.  aagriculture history.  aagriculture.  aasian long bean.  aatlantic slave trade.  ablack history.  acoca cola.  acoffee.  aenvironmental history.  afood and cooking.  afood and culture.  afood history.  afood justice.  afood plots.  afood studies.  afoodways.  aherbal.  amillet.  anature.  anonfiction.  aokra.  apalmolive.  aplantation.  arace.  aslave food.  aslave ships.  aslave trade.  aslavery.  aslaves.  asorghum.  atransatlantic slave trade.  awatermelon.  awest africa.  aworcestershire sauce.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniv